Friday, January 1, 1943

Although out in the evening I got a fair amount of work done today. As of this date the tail length paper, with the exception of a few minor pick-ups, is complete up to the rattler section. The temptation is to drop it now and take up the many taxonomic problems that have lately piled up, including the description of a number of new subspecies. Also I am far behind in card indexing, filing, cataloging and similar activities. But, except for necessary work for other museums and herpetologists, I shall keep on with and try to finish the tail-length study, while the methods and for miles are still fresh in mind.

Saturday, January 2, 1943

Started on the rattler tail-length
studies, also miscellaneous
clean-up work in the basement
taking care of various loans. Got
a considerable lot done.

Sunday, January 3, 1943

Spent the entire day in the basement
checking various specimens and
other miscellaneous work left undone these
many weeks. Checked Bogert's Sonora
rattlers. Wrote this material up in the
evening.

Saturday, January 30, 1943

Worked part of the day on rattler tail correlations.
Went to a Stowkowski concert in
the afternoon.
In the evening ensign Milton Irvine
called. Gave me some lizards from
San Clemente island. We had an
interesting visit. He is a VC entomological
graduate.

Finished the short paper begun yesterday -- then continued with the analytic study of the rattler tail lengths. Worked all day and evening on this and

Monday, February 8, 1943

Went to the meeting of the fellows SDSNH and heard a too-long talk on guayule by Osborn. While dozing I had an idea on showing the difference of a specimen from 2 related species by co-ordinates representing probabilities. Think it is a useful scheme and will drop everything and follow it up.

Monday, March 1, 1943

The tail-length paper is finished; now I shall try to find an avenue of publication, or store it in the safe until after the war. It is necessary to keep finished papers
separate from the mass of data at home out of which no one but myself could ever made head or tail.
After mature consideration I have decided to try to complete
the correlation paper which was started a year and a half ago(9-11-41) and which was interrupted to do the tail-length off-shoot. 125 typewritten pages are finished and much computation and it would seem poor judgment not to complete this (it will take months) before tackling the descriptions of the new species and subspecies which I have on the hook. But the latter surely look attractive and restful.

Saturday, March 6, 1943

Today I started back on the main correlation paper-cleaning up new unfinished items and incorporating new items picked up since last summer, when it was dropped to tackle tail-lengths. Made good progress - finished bilateral symmetry and added some lizard scale counts.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, March 7, 1943

Made more good progress today making the program for overhauling the correlation paper. Spent a lot of time making 8 more correlation studies on ventrals
vs subcaudals.
A pair of ruber were found mating near Sweet water lake. They were brought in to the Zoo.

Saturday, March 91, 1943

Spent most of the morning at the Zoo. Saw the room constructed for the specimens to be removed from the Natural History Museum which is no practically dismantled.
Went over the tail-length paper with Perkins. Mrs Benchley agreed to print it.
Spent the rest of the day on morphological correlations and
made some progress.

Saturday, April 3, 1943

Worked all day on correlation between subcaudal scales and tail length proportion. Fair Progress.
Out in the evening

Page Edit History:
  • jrabbers 07/13/2011 04:16 PM

Sunday, April 4, 1943

Worked all day and evening on correlation between tail-length and subcaudal scales. discovered for the first time that there is a relatively high correlation between subcaudals and the length of tail (in mm. not T/B) in broods. Think this is quite a nobel idea. Finished this section of the paper.

Saturday, April 17, 1943

Worked all day and evening on the correlation paper and it is now practically finished with the exception of the usual checking also bibliography, acknowledgments and summary. This paper was begun 9-11-41 so it took about 1 1/2 years ith time out for the tail-length interlude. I think i had best quit statistics for a while now and go back to taxonomy. But first I shall really clean up the correlation paper ready for Perkins review and then publication if any avenue is open.

Page Edit History:
  • jrabbers 07/13/2011 04:23 PM
  • jrabbers 07/13/2011 04:23 PM
  • tburress 02/25/2011 05:02 PM
  • BPOC 01/12/2011 07:57 PM

Sunday, April 18, 1943,

Worked all day and evening putting the finishing touches on the correlation paper, as I discovered last evening some material on variations with age that had been worked up by Shorty and Omar that hadn't been done yet. Also did bibliography summary and acknowledgments. I hope it will stay done. A very full day's work with plenty accomplished.
Now for a taxonomic vacation.

Tuesday, April 20, 1943

Went to El Cajon Rotary this noon.Out by way of Fletcher Hills; back via Broadway 30 miles. Nothing seen.

April 21 continued.
The moon came up at 9:15. almost full

1 Sidewinder L DOR10milesS.ofKramer Jnct (saved)
1 Arizona S. COR9"""" 9:45 68 degrees

1 Scute L COR Kramer Hills 9:55 66 degrees
Turned around at 10 P.M. at north edge of Kramer Hills. Cold and quite a breeze blowing.
1 SidewinderLCOR19miN.ofAdelanto10:05 62 degrees
1 "L"14""""10:20 66 degrees

(No wind now)
1 sidwinder L DOR squirming 3 mi. N. of Adelanto
Reached Adelanto at 11 and Millers
Corner at 11:30. Riverside at 12:30 and turned in at 1:20 after fixing specimens.
Total miles night collecting drive. 73; time 3 1\4 hour. Pacific war time.
Just before reaching Millers Corner Homer and Bound discovered there was no oil pressure. Valves made quite a clatter. Drove home with much misgivings coasted as much as possible. made it ok.

Wednesday, April 21, 1943

Today started for Riverside with GG at 1:30 P.M. Clear and warm. Went via US 395. Co. line 66 miles
Nothing seen to here.
1 gopher L. DOR 2 miles S. of Temecula grass Brush. saved.
1 gopher M DOR 6 miles NW. of Temecula grass
1 Red racer M. DOR Elsinore Jnct. grass brownish color
1 Red racer L DOR Elsinore Jnct. grass red color.
1 gopher S. DOR North Elsinore jnct grass
Picked up Shorty and David at Riverside.
Started from San Bernadino at 6:45
Clear and warm. Not yet sundown
Reached Miller's corner at 7:45. Sundown. Breezy, cool, a few clouds. moon not up.

1 smallscute COR 8mi.S.ofAdelanto7:55 69 degrees
1 large" COR 8"N""8:30 68 degrees

A cool breeze blowing.

Sunday, April 25, 1943

Worked all day on the Charina problem and almost finished it. Wrote the paper. Spent the evening on miscellaneous catching up.
--------------------------------------
Jim Deuel's trip with Carl Engler
(second day).
Hiked around the foothills about 3 miles N.E
of Barstow. At 9:10 a.m. found a sidewinder neatly coiled in the sand, exposed to the sun It was reluctant to move until touched. while hunting for Sauromalus (saw 2) found a Trimorphodon in a crevice, behind a thick chunk of rock. also found a platyrhinos
Evening drive
1 Sute L COR Hinckley 6:10 68 degrees
1 Longnose DOR Eads
1 Sidewinder DOR 2 miles. W. of Haives. still wiggling at 6:55
Kramer Jnct. after sunset 7:40 P.M. hard wind 57 degrees.
Adelanto at 9:12 62 degrees nothing seen 39 miles 1 1/2 hours. too cold.

Friday, June 25, 1943

Started at 10:30 this morning to attend a California Power Pool conference in Los Angeles. A clear warm day.
1 Red racer L. DOR Stuart grass
2 gophers L. DOR Agra grass (county line 55 miles)
The meeting lasted from 3 to 5:15
1 Red racer L. DOR Vincent, LA co., Lt. brush. Sundown at Rosamond 8:00P.M.
Started east from Mohave at 8:30. Dusk.
A cold hard wind blowing.
1 small scute DOR (squirming-saved)
Boron siding, Kern Co. 9:45 73 degrees
Reached Kramer Junction at 10:07 cold

1 small scute DOR4 mi.S.ofKramer jnct.
1 coleonyx DOR9 """"
1 gopher S. DOR 13 """" (saved)

1coleonyxCOR15 mi.N.ofAdelanto10:45 68 degrees
1""11 """"10:55 68 degrees
1Sonora LDOR5 """"11:10 (saved)
1Arizona LDOR2 "S""

Reached Riverside at 12:50. Found the key to the auto-court cottage pinned to the office door, which was a great relief.
(continued on June 26th)

Saturday, June 9.6, 1943

Spent the day visiting with Shorty in Riverside. a warm day
_____________________________________________
June 25th continued.
A very disappointing evening. No moon. Either too cold or too late in the season.
Miles evening of drive 70. time 2:45 hr. Total miles today 338..

Page Edit History:

Sunday, June 27, 1943

Today we started for Los Angeles at 9. met Howard Hill and Chas. Lowe, Jr. at the Los Angeles museum at 11:00. Looked at specimens until 3:00. Then gave a general talk on snakes before a crowd of about 150. Seemed to go ok. Lowe told me fewer mammals are out on the desert on moonlit night Started for home at 4:45 and reached there at 8:30. Picked up 2 marines and a sailor. Traveled too fast to count the trip.
1 Boyles K M DOR Agra grass. Saw Artran and Bilderback at the meeting today.

Sunday, August 1, 1943

Worked all day on Coleonyx plus miscellaneous curatorial work. Made a little headway doping out important differential characters - - getting oriented, and made some headway. The Tucson population begins to stand out by reason of the high number of preanal pores in the males and also the relatively wide mental must send away for a lot of stuff.

Saturday, August 14, 1943

Spent the evening getting all Coleonyx data so far accumulated properly arranged.
Counted SDSNH and UCLA specimens. Other borrowed material is still awaited.

Sunday, August 15, 1943

Spent most of the day on Coleonyx localities and got them
pretty well worked up.
Then rechecked the coastal and desert specimens in southern california. I think the segregation in most cases (adults especially) is so easy and clear that the coastal one should
be ok.
Company for supper tonight progress today was somewhat delayed by the non-arrival of material from other museums. Hope it gets here during the next week.

Sunday, September 12, 1943

Worked all day (but not evening)on Coleonyx variegatus utahensis. Got this pretty well worked out, but it took a full day.
A Lieut Livingston called tonight and advised me of the death of Harold T. Woodall on Sept. 3rd. He was landing a plane on a carrier when a hook broke at the plane went overboard.

Friday, December 31, 1943

Out to dinner and midnight party tonight.
Thus ends a year characterized by slowly developing papers and hence considerable disappointment with respect to total production. But of course the extra work by reason of war work was considerable. And with the loss of Shaw and Menzies the curatorial work which I must do myself is very time - consuming.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
